Author::::misterbaxter
DateTime::::2016-03-07T19:02:39Z
In practice, there is a fair bit of space between the rows of panels, so that the ground beneath is in partial shade rather than total shade, on the whole. Some grass grows although not at anywhere near the same rate as in a open field. Grazing is ok to keep that grass down, but you'd have to stock at a hugely lower density, or just run the beasts through occasionally.Where this does have potential is in allowing some interesting marginal ecosystems to emerge - the kind of thing you'd get in woodland clearings or around traditional hedgerows. There are lots of species that have suffered hugely from loss of these kinds of habitats, and it would be great if this potential was used to help them to recover somewhat.



