Author::::misterbaxter
DateTime::::2016-03-07T12:29:49Z
I did some work on the planning policy angle of this a while back. Once the sites have been in place for a few years, the ground beneath can actually form some quite rich and interesting habitats. It's basically partial shade, similar to woodland margins, and if it's managed right it can support a lot of otherwise rare species. I really applaud this initiative, the potential is huge for some species that have been badly hit by contemporary farming practices.



